            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Sasha Rostova\u2019s story began not in San Francisco, but in the waning days of the Soviet Union. She arrived in the Richmond District with her parents at age seven, a small girl overwhelmed by the fog and the relentless optimism of 1980s America. Her parents, both engineers, embraced their new life with stoic determination, instilling in Sasha a deep-seated value for stability and hard work. They pushed her toward a safe career, and she dutifully enrolled in a Hospitality Management program at City College, a practical but passionless path.\n\nThe turning point came during a shift at the upscale Japanese restaurant where she was waitressing to pay for classes. The restaurant's owner, an exacting man named Mr. Tanaka, saw her sharp palate and quiet curiosity. He began schooling her in the art of sake, explaining the intricate dance of rice, water, and koji. For Sasha, it was a revelation. Here was a craft steeped in tradition, nuance, and history\u2014a world away from hotel spreadsheets. She dropped out of college, trading formal education for an apprenticeship under his wing.\n\nHer career became her life's work. She devoured books, attended every tasting she could, and saved for a two-week pilgrimage to a small brewery outside Kyoto. Her encyclopedic knowledge and unpretentious approach earned her a reputation. Now 44, Sasha is the respected Bar Manager and Sake Sommelier at a chic Izakaya in Hayes Valley.\n\nHer life is measured by the city\u2019s rhythm. Her day starts late in her small, neat apartment in the Lower Haight, usually with tea and a book. The 3.5-mile crosstown Muni ride is her time to decompress before the evening rush. Her social life is woven into her profession; her closest friends are chefs, fellow sommeliers, and longtime regulars. Relationships have been fleeting, often secondary to the demanding hours of her career.\n\nSasha feels intrinsically tied to this version of San Francisco\u2014the one built on craft, taste, and community, not code. Her quiet ambition is to one day open her own place: a tiny, 20-seat sake bar in a neighborhood like the Inner Sunset, a tribute to the city that gave her a home and a calling."
